---
description: Persistent memory handling and concise memory indexing
alwaysApply: true
---

After each turn, update memory deliberately and minimally.

**`.cursor/memory/MEMORY.md`** must remain high signal in its *index* sections (prefs, decisions, pointers). **Operational continuation** lives in **`.cursor/memory/memories/YYYY-MM-DD-continuation.md`** (one file per UTC day)—append there rather than duplicating runbooks.

Store in the index portions of **`.cursor/memory/MEMORY.md`** only:

- durable user instructions
- durable user preferences
- standing directives
- major pivot decisions
- high-level architecture notes
- references to important dependent files with exact paths

Do not store in the index portions of **`.cursor/memory/MEMORY.md`** (use **`*-continuation.md`**, other `memories/` files, or runbooks as appropriate):

- verbose project logs
- chains of attempted fixes
- blocker narratives
- runbook-level detail
- detailed execution history

When adding a new durable index-style item, prepend it to the top of **`.cursor/memory/MEMORY.md`**.

Detailed project-specific context belongs in timestamped files under:

- `.cursor/memory/memories/YYYY-MM-DD-continuation.md` (per-day ops)
- `.cursor/memory/memories/YYYY-MM-DD_HHMM_<topic>.md` (topic-specific)

Each memory file should preserve concise but complete continuity for a topic or work session, including when relevant:

- what was being worked on
- context
- processes performed
- protocols followed
- actions taken
- files touched
- blockers found
- blockers resolved
- blockers still persisting
- outcomes
- next relevant state

Do not bloat the main memory file with content that belongs in detailed memory files.

